<DocsLayout title="Quick Start" description="Start saving tokens in 2 minutes.">
  <p>
    This guide gets you from zero to saving tokens in the shortest possible time.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1: Install</h2>
  <pre><code># Homebrew (macOS)
brew tap yvgude/tap && brew install lean-ctx

# Or via crates.io
cargo install lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h2>Step 2: Set Up Shell Hook</h2>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx init --global</code></pre>
  <p>Installs 23 aliases for git, npm, cargo, docker, kubectl, gh, pip, ruff, eslint, curl, and more.</p>

  <h2>Step 3: Configure Your Editor</h2>
  <p>For Cursor, add to <code>~/.cursor/mcp.json</code>:</p>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "lean-ctx": {
      "command": "lean-ctx"
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Step 4: Restart and Verify</h2>
  <p>Restart your editor. The lean-ctx tools will appear in the MCP tool list.</p>

  <p>Test the shell hook from the terminal:</p>
  <pre><code>git status
lean-ctx gain</code></pre>

  <p>
    Inside your editor, use the <code>ctx_benchmark</code> MCP tool on any file
    to see token savings for each compression strategy.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 5: Monitor Savings</h2>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx gain
lean-ctx dashboard</code></pre>

  <p>
    <code>lean-ctx gain</code> shows cumulative token savings in the terminal.
    <code>lean-ctx dashboard</code> opens a web dashboard at <code>localhost:3333</code>
    with interactive charts, KPIs, and per-tool breakdowns.
    For per-session stats inside your editor, use <code>ctx_metrics</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 6: Analyze Adoption</h2>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx discover
lean-ctx session</code></pre>
  <p>
    <code>lean-ctx discover</code> scans your shell history for commands that could benefit from compression.
    <code>lean-ctx session</code> shows your adoption rate.
  </p>

